{"title": "Iranian director wins Oscar, but skips awards show over Trump\u2019s \u2018inhumane\u2019 travel ban - The Boston Globe", "url": "https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/television/2017/02/26/iranian-director-wins-oscar-but-skips-awards-show-over-trump-inhumane-travel-ban/Hvdbx9c8SU55FdV5IHvCCI/story.html", "text": "Chris Pizzello/Invision/AP Anousheh Ansari accepted the award for best foreign language film for \"The Salesman\" on behalf of Asghar Farhadi at the Oscars on Sunday.\n\nThe 2017 Academy Awards After a stunning mixup, \u2018Moonlight\u2019 awarded best picture How the 'Moonlight'-'La La Land' scene unfolded Plenty of sympathy to go around Pricewaterhouse Coopers apologizes for role in miscue Look at who wowed on the red carpet Host Jimmy Kimmel blends political humor with Hollywood teasing Trump was on people\u2019s minds, if not lips, at Oscars Damien Chazelle\u2019s Harvard professors remember him when Hollywood tour group gets surprise side trip to Oscar show Kimmel-Matt Damon \u2018feud\u2019 spills across the Oscars stage Winning Iranian director skips show over \u2018inhumane\u2019 travel ban Stars wear blue ribbons in support of ACLU Sting pays an emotional tribute to slain N.H. journalist James Foley In Rhode Island, fans cheer native Viola Davis's win Sound engineer wins first Oscar after 21 nominations Notable moments from the 2017 Oscars \u2014 other than that one List of winners at the 89th Academy Awards\n\nThe Iranian director of \u201cThe Salesman\u201d won his second Academy Award Sunday night, but skipped the show in protest of President Donald Trump\u2019s travel ban for immigrants from Iran and six other nations.\n\nAsghar Farhadi won the Oscar for best foreign-language film, but instead of accepting the award himself, he had a representative read a statement that slammed Trump\u2019s policy.\n\nAdvertisement\n\n\u201cMy absence is out of respect for the people of my country and those of the other six nations whom have been disrespected by the inhumane law that bans entry of immigrants to the US,\u201d according to Farhadi \u2018s statement, which was read by Anousheh Ansari, who is famed for being the first female space tourist.\n\n\u201cDividing the world into the \u2018us\u2019 and the \u2018enemy\u2019 categories creates fear. A deceitful justification for aggression and war. These wars prevent democracy and human rights in countries which have themselves been victims of aggression,\u201d according to Farhadi\u2019s statement.\n\nGet The Weekender in your inbox: The Globe's top picks for what to see and do each weekend, in Boston and beyond. Sign Up Thank you for signing up! Sign up for more newsletters here\n\nIt was previously reported that Ansari, and Dr. Firouz Naderi, director of Solar Systems Exploration at NASA, would Farhadi\u2019s representatives at this year\u2019s Academy Awards.\n\nThe statement did not refer to Trump by name.\n\nFarhadi had announced in January that would not attend the ceremony, even if exceptions were made for him.\n\nAdvertisement\n\nIn his statement, he said filmmakers help break down stereotypes and create empathy between people, something that \u201cwe need today more than ever.\u201d", "source": "BostonGlobe.com", "publish_date": "2017-02-26", "type": "article"}